Poland and space.
Last week at meeting of ministers of the European space agency Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European space agency as the second country from the countries of the former east block (after the Czech Republic which became the full member of EKA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with EKA in 1994 and within the next years took active part in a number of projects of agency.
But to space Poland began a way much earlier.
Even before World War II the Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights to space, but it not always met understanding.
I will remind, for example, of lecture of A.Shternfeld who presented on December 6, 1933 in the Warsaw astronomical observatory of idea from the innovative work "Introduction to astronautics".
Ideas of the young engineer (1905) left audience indifferent, after several years Shternfeld remembered that only doctor Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934 in France Shternfeld won Robert Esno-Peltri and André Luisa Hirsh's award for "Introduction in astronautics".
Doctor Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966) about whom it was spoken above, became the great propagandist of astronomy and astronautics later.
It published in the Polish magazines of one hundred articles and wrote a number of the books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky I became the known world propagandist of astronautics, and his contribution was estimated including that one of craters on a reverse side of the Moon was called in his honor.
In 1925 in Poland the railway section car equipped with the rocket engine was constructed.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained is unknown, as well as project details.
Not it is clear even, for dispersal or for braking of the cart the rocket had to be used.
Information on this section car is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933 the Polish artillery started reflecting on rocket arrows.
Research was carried out by Section of equipment of arms at cooperation with professors Mieczyslaw Volfka and Gustav Mokzhitskim.
From the remained materials it is visible that researches reached a stage of practical tests.
But with arrival of the German armies of work were interrupted.
In 1937 in the specialized press there was an idea of the photo-electric rocket fighter which was offered by the engineer Rogozinsky, and next year there was a work "The air rocket torpedo and the aviation rocket bomb" the author Lelivy-Kzhivoblotsky.
Both projects were developed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war by all projects of military use of rocketry the Interim scientific and advisory committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) which coordinated all work was engaged.
The committee was created in 1937, but after two years of the activity work ended because of the war beginning.
The following scientific work devoted to astronautics, appeared in the Polish press after war, thanks to work of the Polish society of astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time society it is mentioned in November issue of 1954 of the Problemy magazine in which four volume articles on astronautics are published.
In one of them professor of M. Subotovich suggested to organize society which will go in for astronautics.
At that time already projects of artificial satellites grew, and it was clear that space researches - perspective branch.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish society of astronautics (PSA) tried to enter the international federation of astronautics (based in 1951), and in the fall of POA became her full member.
And next year the first chairman of POA Kazimezh Zarankevich (1902 - 1959) became the vice-chairman of the International federation of astronautics.
At this position it remained to the most death which came in 1959.
Since 1956 of POA made the significant contribution to development of very successful meteorological RM rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) which became the first Polish rocket which has executed scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was complete in 1957, and the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, capable to overcome distance of 1800 m, was in length about 80 cm, and its weight made less than 5 kg.
Subsequently the advanced RM-1A version was constructed, and in the summer of 1959 on the Bledovsky waste ground tests of the two-level RM-2 rocket were carried out.
This rocket was in length about 1,4 m, and its weight made about 11,5 kg.
The following version of the rocket was already able to be engaged in the real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could overcome 14,5 km, and supervision over a high-rise wind was its task.
But in 1962 further development was suspended.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period between 1962 and 1965 became the successor of the first RM rockets.
The rocket was conceived as two-level, its total length made 510 cm, and initial weight - 32,5 kg.
Three types (designated as the Meteor-1А, - 1B and - 1C) which differed with the camera size for the scientific equipment were developed.
The Meteor-1А rocket had space of 0,4 l, the Meteor-1В - 0,34 l, and the Meteor-1С - 0,62л.
The maximum range of flight all three types had 37 km.
During the period between 1965 and 1968 in Aviation institute there took place development of the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October, 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a starting weight of 380 kg was capable to bring a payload weighing 10 kg to height about 60 km.
Then Meteor-2Н versions and the Meteor-3 were constructed.
It is worth mentioning also the entry of Poland in KOSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and KOSPAR national committee creation by two years later.
Besides, within the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space researches on the Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second Vladimir Remek's interkosmonavty ambassador.
