In the research "Unoccupied reason: boredom definition from the point of view of attention", published in September issue of the Perspectives on Psychological Science magazine, professor Eastwood with colleagues refer to the experiment made earlier which participants listened to record of the voice reading the magazine.
One participants heard also loud sounds of the irrelevant TV program included in the neighboring room, others heard the same sounds on low the loudness so they could be sorted, and the third group listened only to record of a voice without a foreign sound track.
Those participants who heard the TV with low level of loudness, noted that it was boring for them, is more often than others - it was difficult to them to concentrate, but they didn't know the reason of it and attributed it to boredom.
